class Solution {
    public int getMaxRepetitions(String s1, int n1, String s2, int n2) {
        int len1 = s1.length(), len2 = s2.length();
        int[] repeatCnt = new int[len2 + 1];
        int[] nextIdx = new int[len2 + 1];
        int j = 0, cnt = 0;
        for (int k = 1; k <= n1; k++) {
            for (int i = 0; i < len1; i++) {
                if (s1.charAt(i) == s2.charAt(j)) {
                    j++;
                    if (j == len2) {
                        cnt++;
                        j = 0;
                    }
                }
            }
            repeatCnt[k] = cnt;
            nextIdx[k] = j;
            for (int start = 0; start < k; start++) {
                if (nextIdx[start] == j) {
                    int prevCnt = repeatCnt[start];
                    int patternCnt = (repeatCnt[k] - repeatCnt[start]) * ((n1 - start) / (k - start));
                    int remainCnt = repeatCnt[start + (n1 - start) % (k - start)] - repeatCnt[start];
                    return (prevCnt + patternCnt + remainCnt) / n2;
                }
            }
        }
        return cnt / n2;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O((len1 + len2) * min(n1, len2))
space complexity: O(len2)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses pattern detection to avoid simulating all n1 copies of s1. Tracks how many full copies of s2 are found per s1 block and the next starting index in s2. When a cycle is detected, computes the total occurrences via arithmetic, then divides by n2 to get the maximum m.

